[2] Unity and Upper Nile states
Date: Fri 4 Jul 2014
Source: Radio Tamazuj [edited]
https://radiotamazuj.org/en/article/cholera-spreads-unity-and-upper-nile-states


South Sudan's cholera outbreak is worsening with reports of outbreaks in overcrowded and unsanitary camps in Unity and Upper Nile states. There are now hundreds of suspected cholera cases in Bentiu [Unity State], Wau Shilluk [Upper Nile State], and Malakal [Upper Nile State], in addition to the thousands of cases in Juba [Central Equatoria State] and Eastern Equatoria State, according to the latest weekly situation report by the UN's Office for Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA).

OCHA reported a possible outbreak in Wau Shilluk, Upper Nile State, where 246 suspected cases were reported in only 72 hours.

Aid agencies set up a cholera treatment center in Wau Shilluk, a small village about an hour downstream of Malakal where about 39 000 displaced people are sheltering, with oral rehydration and handwashing stations and distributed soap and hygiene kits.

Earlier this week [week of 30 Jun 2014], humanitarian agency Oxfam reported one case of cholera in the Malakal UN base. In the Bentiu UN base, there were 11 suspected cholera cases and one death. OCHA said samples are still being confirmed to see if it is indeed cholera.

OCHA said over 100 new latrines were constructed in Bentiu to improve sanitation in the congested camp, though they need nearly 500 more to reach the international standard of one latrine for every 50 people. The report said that cholera response supplies need replenishment in Eastern Equatoria and Upper Nile states, and that there are 9 cholera treatment centers in Juba, where nearly 2000 cholera cases have been reported since May 2014.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[From its origin in Juba in Central Equatoria State, the cholera outbreak continues to spread east and north in the country. - Mod.LL

